column4: many of whom were actresses and models. millions of women have used the feminist hashtag
column5: many also sharing their stories of how they have survived sexual violence or manipulation. it took the internet by such force and has brought the conversation about sexual harassment to the forefront.

column1: i‚Äôm extremely fortunate that in both my personal and professional life i‚Äôm able to contribute to work that has meaning and serves a greater purpose
column2: but this particular project is really something special.
@elizahatch and i met in person to discuss the possibility of a collaborative project between @unfpa and her photojournalism series @cheerupluv
column3: which is dedicated to combating the normalization of sexual harassment. sri lanka immediately came to mind because the findings from a study commissioned by unfpa were still fresh on my mind: 90% of women in sri lanka endure sexual harassment on public buses and trains.

column2: because it certainly did for us. and knowing that there are real people behind those numbers is probably what kept us and @zootapes_ going while filming on-location in colombo in sweltering 90¬∞+ heat in some of the most crowded (and sometimes unwelcome) public spaces you can imagine; on at least one occasion we somehow managed to film five different women in five different locations between sunrise and sunset in one day.
i‚Äôm so glad that the world now finally gets to see what we‚Äôve been working tirelessly on. the 16 women who bravely shared their stories are the real mvps
column3: but i‚Äôm also forever indebted to @zootapes_ and @elizahatch for their unrelenting work and creative spirits
column4: and for unintentionally making a lifelong dream of mine come true: seeing my name in the credit line for a film üé•

column2: please hit the link in my bio or head on over to unfpa.org/16days to learn more.‚òùüèø

column1: 248573;instagram;2018-11-24 23:01:41;FALSE;"i know at this time of year we get inundated with charity requests and often feel guilty about the mass consumerism that goes with christmas.

@sharethedignityaustralia has a beautiful initiate called #itsinthebag. ‚Äúyou have the power to make life better for a woman or girl experiencing homelessness or poverty this christmas. provide pads and tampons
column2: personal hygiene products and everyday luxuries to homeless women
column3: women at risk or women experiencing domestic violence.‚Äù üíú

column1: find a handbag you no longer use or buy a new one and pop in some ‚Äòluxuries‚Äô most of us take for granted everyday. makes me so sad to think women out there who are already feeling worthless and unloved
column2: cannot even have the dignity of everyday hygiene products. go through your cupboards and clear out that lotion you never opened or the makeup palette that wasn‚Äôt your colours and pass it on. make a woman or teen girl feel important this christmas. add some toothpaste / soap / shampoo and all of a sudden someone doesn‚Äôt feel like a no-one anymore. üëõ

column1: 248606;instagram;2018-11-25 00:00:51;FALSE;". claim all of who you are!
i've traveled the globe and lived in the usa
all over the world women are treated as second-class citizens. patriarchy has its hold on humanity.
from my research and my travels
column2: i've discovered the best way to shift patriarchy is to start within your own body.

column1: discover all the places inside where you feel second-rate. .
shift those energetic thoughts to how worthy you really are. .

column2: inside i felt like a miserable bigger.

column1: and then there was the guilt.

column2: if i kept myself small enough then it would be ok.

column3: if i shut down small enough into a little teeny box

column1: that's how i was taught to be a woman.

column2: the only way for me to make a difference in this world is to expand into who i really am. .

column1: so that i can inspire you to claim all of you.
the world needs all of who you are right now!
tag a friend that will like to read this.

248664;instagram;2018-11-25 02:19:28;FALSE;tonight i wanna talk about something that has recently been dug up in my mind again.
when i was 9 years old i participated in an after school program where i met a boy who was older than me. he was always really nice to me. i didn‚Äôt see anything wrong with it at the time
column2: i was just happy to be friends with a ‚Äúbig kid.‚Äù one day on the playground everyone left and he showed me some cool toy that he had. he said i could have it if i let him touch me. thinking he was going in for a hug i obliged
column3: but he didn‚Äôt want a hug. he felt me
